<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="418" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,1807,2013]" pageId="17" pageNumber="418">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,286,1807,1833]" pageId="17" pageNumber="418">Etymology.</emphasis>
The genus is composed of the Greek “ 
<emphasis box="[713,787,1807,1833]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="418">Astron</emphasis>
” for star and the Greek “glypho” for “carved or engraved” alluding to the very sculpted appearance of both species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="418" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,1807,2013]" pageId="17" pageNumber="418">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1878,1904]" pageId="17" pageNumber="418">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Body petaloid with short, blunt, arms. Disk and arm ossicles enlarged, convex and blocky forming three distinct series with carinal and superomarginal plates visible along each arm. Disk plates enlarged and blocky. Surface covered by continuous granulation. Adambulacral spines one or two. Large flattened bullet-shaped subambulacral spine present.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="419" type="type_taxon">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,150,1437]" box="[199,719,150,177]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,354,150,177]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">
<typeStatus box="[199,258,151,177]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Type</typeStatus>
species.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Mah" authorityName="Mah" authorityYear="2021" box="[361,649,151,177]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" genus="Tamaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="pyramidata" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[361,591,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Tamaria pyramidata</emphasis>
Mah
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[657,719,151,177]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[657,719,151,177]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,150,1437]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,476,186,212]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Taxonomic Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Downey" authorityYear="1971" box="[485,700,187,213]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" genus="Tamaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="passiflora">
<emphasis box="[485,700,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Tamaria passiflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the new species of 
<taxonomicName authority="Mah, 2021" authorityName="Mah" authorityYear="2021" box="[980,1116,187,213]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Astroglypha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[980,1116,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Astroglypha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1125,1205,187,213]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1125,1205,187,213]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
fall outside the historical 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1840" box="[231,325,223,248]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" genus="Tamaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[231,325,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Tamaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
concept as outlined by H.L. 
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, H. L." box="[660,805,223,249]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" pagination="1 - 223" refId="ref27565" refString="Clark, H. L. (1921) The echinoderm fauna of Torres Strait: its composition and its origin. Department of Marine Biology of the Carnegie Institute, 10, i - vi + 1 - 223, 38 pls. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 14613" type="journal article" year="1921">Clark (1921)</bibRefCitation>
and are herein assigned to the new genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mah" authorityYear="2021" box="[1293,1429,223,249]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Astroglypha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1293,1429,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Astroglypha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1870" box="[203,380,259,285]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="family">Ophidiasteridae</taxonomicName>
has recently undergone re-evaluation following molecular data (
<bibRefCitation author="Mah, C. L. &amp; Foltz, D. W." box="[1112,1326,259,285]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" pagination="769 - 788" refId="ref30190" refString="Mah, C. L. &amp; Foltz, D. W. (2011) Molecular Phylogeny of the Valvatacea (Asteroidea, Echinodermata). Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society, 161, 769 - 788. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1096 - 3642.2010.00659. x" type="journal article" year="2011">Mah &amp; Foltz 2011</bibRefCitation>
) showing genera such as 
<taxonomicName box="[321,404,295,320]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Fromia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[321,404,295,320]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Fromia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Livingstone" authorityYear="1931" box="[458,583,295,321]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Neoferdina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[458,583,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Neoferdina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to be members of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Forbes" authorityYear="1841" box="[832,991,295,321]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="family">Goniasteridae</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Mah, C. L." box="[1002,1134,295,321]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" pagination="1 - 72" refId="ref30028" refString="Mah, C. L. (2017) Overview of the Ferdina - like Goniasteridae (Echinodermata: Asteroidea) including a new subfamily, three new genera and fourteen new species. Zootaxa, 4271 (1) 1 - 72. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4271.1.1" type="journal article" year="2017">Mah (2017)</bibRefCitation>
examined the paraphyletic 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1870" box="[151,328,331,357]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="family">Ophidiasteridae</taxonomicName>
and attempted to establish morphological boundaries for ophidiasterid-like 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Forbes" authorityYear="1841" box="[1171,1327,331,357]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="family">Goniasteridae</taxonomicName>
and more typological 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1870" box="[284,464,367,393]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="family">Ophidiasteridae</taxonomicName>
, such as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Ziesenhenne" baseAuthorityYear="1963" box="[564,698,367,393]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" genus="Ophidiaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[564,698,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Ophidiaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nardo" authorityYear="1834" box="[735,819,367,393]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" genus="Linckia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[735,819,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Linckia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,150,1437]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1840" box="[199,293,403,428]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" genus="Tamaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[199,293,403,428]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Tamaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been historically defined on the basis of six serial papular rows contingent on the absence of actinal papulae, as compared with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Ziesenhenne" baseAuthorityYear="1963" box="[497,631,439,465]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" genus="Ophidiaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[497,631,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Ophidiaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(H.L. 
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, H. L." box="[705,841,439,465]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" pagination="1 - 223" refId="ref27565" refString="Clark, H. L. (1921) The echinoderm fauna of Torres Strait: its composition and its origin. Department of Marine Biology of the Carnegie Institute, 10, i - vi + 1 - 223, 38 pls. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 14613" type="journal article" year="1921">Clark, 1921</bibRefCitation>
). However, in spite of the difference in papular rows, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1840" box="[151,245,475,500]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" genus="Tamaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,245,475,500]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Tamaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in Clark’s original (1921) definition shares more characters with more typological ophidiasterids, such as 
<taxonomicName authority="(sensu Mah 2017)" baseAuthorityName="sensu Mah" baseAuthorityYear="2017" box="[151,500,511,537]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" genus="Ophidiaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,285,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Ophidiaster</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[302,364,511,536]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">sensu</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Mah, C. L." box="[373,492,511,537]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" pagination="1 - 72" refId="ref30028" refString="Mah, C. L. (2017) Overview of the Ferdina - like Goniasteridae (Echinodermata: Asteroidea) including a new subfamily, three new genera and fourteen new species. Zootaxa, 4271 (1) 1 - 72. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4271.1.1" type="journal article" year="2017">Mah 2017</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, such as the cylindrical arms, small disk and marginal and abactinal plate arrangement.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,150,1437]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Downey" authorityYear="1971" box="[199,412,583,609]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" genus="Tamaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="passiflora">
<emphasis box="[199,412,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Tamaria passiflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Downey, M." box="[620,796,583,609]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" pagination="43 - 50" refId="ref27912" refString="Downey, M. (1971) Two new species of the genus Tamaria (Echinodermata: Asteroidea) from the tropical western Atlantic. Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington, 84 (5), 43 - 50." type="journal article" year="1971">Downey (1971)</bibRefCitation>
with four papular rows as well as a more strongly developed skeleton, petaloid-shaped, shorter arms and a more weakly stellate body (R/r = approximately 3.0–4.0 versus 4.0–7.0 in spp. more similar to the 
<typeStatus box="[557,605,655,681]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">type</typeStatus>
species) and large blocky marginal and disk ossicles. These features are inconsistent with characters identifying the traditional 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1840" box="[768,862,691,716]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" genus="Tamaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[768,862,691,716]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Tamaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
concept as outlined by H.L. 
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, H. L." box="[1191,1339,691,717]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" pagination="1 - 223" refId="ref27565" refString="Clark, H. L. (1921) The echinoderm fauna of Torres Strait: its composition and its origin. Department of Marine Biology of the Carnegie Institute, 10, i - vi + 1 - 223, 38 pls. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 14613" type="journal article" year="1921">Clark (1921)</bibRefCitation>
. Thus, it is argued that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Downey" authorityYear="1971" box="[314,529,727,753]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" genus="Tamaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="passiflora">
<emphasis box="[314,529,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Tamaria passiflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the species described herein should be separated as part of the new genus, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mah" authorityYear="2021" box="[151,287,763,789]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Astroglypha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,287,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Astroglypha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Clark, A. M. &amp; Downey, M. E." box="[304,650,763,789]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" refId="ref27203" refString="Clark, A. M. &amp; Downey, M. E. (1992) Starfishes of the Atlantic. Chapman &amp; Hall, London, 794 pp." type="book" year="1992">Clark &amp; Downey (1992: 284)</bibRefCitation>
further discussed this species’ unusual morphology and agreed that “perhaps deserves to be removed to a new genus, on the basis of its single row of large abactinal plates, its irregular arrangement of actinal plates, two series of subambulacral spines, minute terminal plates and short, heavy petaloid arms.”
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,150,1437]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,758,906,933]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">
<taxonomicName authority="Mah, 2021" authorityName="Mah" authorityYear="2021" box="[199,339,906,933]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Astroglypha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,339,906,933]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Astroglypha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[346,424,907,933]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
within the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1870" box="[558,753,906,932]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="family">Ophidiasteridae</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Mah, 2021" authorityName="Mah" authorityYear="2021" box="[765,901,907,933]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Astroglypha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[765,901,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Astroglypha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[907,985,907,933]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[907,985,907,933]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is provisionally placed within the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1870" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="family">Ophidiasteridae</taxonomicName>
but further testing of affinities is encouraged. Most of the genera included in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1870" box="[1172,1349,943,969]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="family">Ophidiasteridae</taxonomicName>
display characters which strongly support the more traditional ophidiasterid morphology. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1840" box="[1071,1160,979,1005]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" genus="Hacelia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1071,1160,979,1005]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Hacelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hayashi" authorityYear="1973" box="[1174,1331,979,1005]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" genus="Heteronardoa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1174,1331,979,1005]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Heteronardoa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Nardo" authorityYear="1834" box="[1345,1429,979,1005]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" genus="Linckia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1345,1429,979,1005]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Linckia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="sensu Mah" baseAuthorityYear="2017" box="[151,285,1015,1041]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" genus="Ophidiaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,285,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Ophidiaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1840" box="[346,440,1015,1040]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" genus="Tamaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[346,440,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Tamaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
display characters with cylindrical arms, small disk, granular coverings and show abactinal and marginal plates which are identical in appearance.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1437,150,1437]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">
The newly described 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mah" authorityYear="2021" box="[438,574,1087,1113]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Astroglypha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[438,574,1087,1113]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Astroglypha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lacks morphological characters seen in other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1870" box="[1083,1263,1087,1113]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="family">Ophidiasteridae</taxonomicName>
, including having shorter arms, blockier abactinal and marginal plates and arms which are more angular in shape and angular rather than round in cross-section. However, marginal and abactinal plates are similar in appearance and the surface is covered by granules as is the case in other ophidiasterids. Thus, based on these characters, 
<taxonomicName authority="Mah, 2021" authorityName="Mah" authorityYear="2021" box="[1190,1326,1195,1221]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Astroglypha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus" status="n. gen.">
<emphasis box="[1190,1326,1195,1221]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Astroglypha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1332,1411,1195,1221]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1332,1411,1195,1221]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" rank="genus">n. gen.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is retained within the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verrill" authorityYear="1870" box="[368,549,1231,1257]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="family">Ophidiasteridae</taxonomicName>
. However, the morphology is otherwise highly divergent from the other known genera within the family with the possible exception of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Doderlein" authorityYear="1896" box="[782,883,1267,1292]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" genus="Bunaster" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[782,883,1267,1292]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Bunaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which displays similarly arranged abactinal and marginal plates (
<bibRefCitation author="Marsh, L. M." box="[345,490,1303,1329]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" pagination="419 - 433" refId="ref30323" refString="Marsh, L. M. (1999) A revision of the echinoderm genus Bunaster (Asteroidea; Ophidiasteridae). Records of the Western Australian Museum, 15 (2), 419 - 433." type="journal article" year="1999">Marsh 1999</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Blake, D. B." box="[513,711,1303,1330]" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" pagination="1 - 96" refId="ref26630" refString="Blake, D. B. (2018) Toward a History of the Paleozoic Asteroidea (Echinodermata). Bulletin of American Paleontology, 394, 1 - 96, 15 pls. https: // doi. org / 10.1130 / abs / 2018 AM- 318490" type="journal article" year="2018">Blake (2018: 60)</bibRefCitation>
illustrated skeletal similarities between 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mah" authorityYear="2021" box="[1182,1318,1303,1329]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Astroglypha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1182,1318,1303,1329]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Astroglypha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(formerly 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1840" box="[151,245,1339,1364]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" genus="Tamaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,245,1339,1364]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Tamaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Downey" authorityYear="1971" box="[265,377,1339,1365]" class="Asteroidea" family="Ophidiasteridae" genus="Tamaria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="passiflora">
<emphasis box="[265,377,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">passiflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and Paleozoic 
<taxonomicName box="[557,681,1339,1365]" class="Asteroidea" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="class">Asteroidea</taxonomicName>
, notably the Ordovician 
<taxonomicName box="[973,1116,1339,1365]" class="Asteroidea" family="Hudsonasteridae" genus="Hudsonaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Asteroidea incertae sedis" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[973,1116,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Hudsonaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[1178,1436,1339,1364]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Raymond" authorityYear="1921" box="[1178,1347,1339,1364]" class="Asteroidea" family="Pustulosida (awaiting allocation)" genus="Macroporaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pustulosida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">Macroporaster</taxonomicName>
. In situ
</emphasis>
observation of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mah" authorityYear="2021" baseAuthorityName="Downey" baseAuthorityYear="2021" box="[318,572,1375,1401]" class="Asteroidea" family="Goniasteridae" genus="Astroglypha" kingdom="Animalia" order="Valvatida" pageId="18" pageNumber="419" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="passiflora">
<emphasis box="[318,572,1375,1401]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Astroglypha passiflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the tropical Atlantic (
<figureCitation box="[842,925,1375,1401]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1858,1882]" captionTargetBox="[158,1430,188,1829]" captionTargetId="figure-15@21.[151,1436,181,1834]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 8. Astroglypha passiflora n. comb. USNM 1233542 (Yucatan Channel, Mexico): A. Abactinal surface. Scale bar equals 0.5 cm. B. Abactinal-lateral view. Scale bar equals 0.35 cm. C. Actinal surface. Scale bar equals 0.5 cm. D. Actinal-lateral view of marginal plate series. Scale bar equals 0.35 cm. E. Actinal view showing actinal spines and furrow spination. Scale bar equals 0.1 cm. F. In situ observation of A. passiflora from Puerto Rico, showing individual (not collected) adjacent to two sponges." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4896913" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4896913/files/figure.png" pageId="18" pageNumber="419">Fig. 8F</figureCitation>
) suggest this morphology could be associated with predation on sponges.
</paragraph>
